<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TEC Demands Suspension of Government Salary Increase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2501160394 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1532 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2501160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria Jan 25 SAPA -- The Transitional Executive 
Council [TEC] on Tuesday demanded the government suspend its 
planned salary increases for senior civil servants. The 
resolution evoked controversy within the TEC as government and 
National Party representatives rejected it. Government 
representative Fanie van der Merwe and the NP's Leon Wessels 
argued the TEC had recommended its finance sub-council 
investigate the increases and report to the TEC next week. Any 
TEC decision on the increases should be made only after the 
sub-council had delivered its report, they argued. 
  The increases were reported in a Sunday newspaper which 
speculated their effect would be to dramatically boost civil 
servants' pensions for retirees after the April elections. Mr 
Van Der Merwe said the TEC had no way of knowing who exactly 
would be affected by its decision. The resolution was carried 
with government and NP disagreement. 

</TEXT>

