<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   IFP Official: Party Committed to New Local Governments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2501192694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1846 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2501192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Durban Jan 25 SAPA -- The kwaZulu government and the 
Inkatha Freedom Party [IFP] were totally committed to full 
participation in new local government structures, senior IFP 
official Peter Miller repeated on Tuesday. Speaking at a local 
government seminar in Durban, Mr Miller said there should be "no 
question" about kwaZulu and the IFP's commitment to the Local 
Government Transition Act which was signed into law last week. 
This was in spite of the IFP and kwaZulu government having 
withdrawn from national negotiations on the act. 
  At the signing of the act last week, Mr Miller caused 
excitement when he said the IFP would "participate fully and 
absolutely in third-tier government". Some political observers 
said his announcement might have paved the way for IFP 
participation in national elections on April 27. However, IFP 
national spokesman Ziba Jiyane said Mr Miller was probably just 
expressing his own "hopeful" opinion. But, speaking in 
Pietermaritzburg on Monday, Mr Miller said IFP leader Mangosuthu 
Buthelezi had personally endorsed his party's full participation 
in new, democratic local government structures. 
  In Durban on Tuesday, Mr Miller said he also had the full 
backing of the kwaZulu government in committing it to 
participation in transitional local government structures. 
"We'll participate fully. We want to be part of the solution, 
not the problem. Let's go into this process together, 
determined to make it work." 
  While Mr Miller is known to support IFP participation in the 
April 27 elections, a final decision on the party's stance will 
become clear only at the weekend at a special general conference 
in Ulundi. 

</TEXT>

