<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Cote d'Ivoire </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Bedie Appoints New Supreme Court President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2501225394 Abidjan Radio Cote d'Ivoire Chaine 
Nationale-Une Network in French 1900 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB2501225394 </F>
<F P=104>  Abidjan Radio Cote d'Ivoire Chaine 
Nationale-Une Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The institutional vacuum created by the 
resignation of Mr. Lanzeni Coulibaly was filled this morning. 
The head of state, His Excellency Henri Konan Bedie, this 
morning appointed a new Supreme Court president. He is Michel 
Koui Mamadou. Soon after his appointment, the new Supreme Court 
president resigned from his post of deputy and announced that he 
would leave the Democratic Party of Cote d'Ivoire-African 
Democratic Rally [PDCI-RDA] because of the new responsibilities 
assigned to him. Here is the new president's statement soon 
after his appointment: 
  [Begin Mamadou recording] His Excellency President Henri 
Konan Bedie has just honored me by appointing me to the high 
office of the president of the Supreme Court of Cote d'Ivoire. 
In this solemn moment, I would like to sincerely thank him for 
fully trusting me--trust that I will strive to further serve. 
[passage omitted] 
  I would like to stress that while accepting the functions of 
president of the high institution that President Henri Konan 
Bedie has assigned to me, I will automatically give up the post 
of deputy that I have been occupying. I cannot be a judge and 
parliamentarian at the same. My resignation is effective 
immediately. Similary, as of today I give up all my functions 
within the PDCI-RDA steering organs because of the neutrality 
demanded by my new responsibilities. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

