<H3> <TI>   Rights Group Expresses Confidence in Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2601085094 Paris AFP in English 2112 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2601085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, 25 Jan (AFP)--The policy making body of the 
human rights group Campaign for Democracy (CD) has passed a vote 
of confidence in its national chairman, after he was accused of 
collaboration with the military. The vote of confidence was 
revealed in a communique issued here Tuesday [25 January] on the 
outcome of an emergency meeting of CD's National Coordination 
Council, held at the weekend in Lagos. 
  Last Tuesday, CD secretary-general Chima Ubani accused 
chairman Beko Ransome-Kuti of "collaborating" with the military 
and "compromising" the CD, the umbrella group for pro-democracy 
and human rights associations in Nigeria. Ransome-Kuti has 
denied the charges. 
  A two-day national convention of the CD is scheduled to 
begin 
February 4, during which issues related to the association's 
internal problems as well as its future approach to national 
matters are expected to be discussed. 

</TEXT>

