<F P=101> Senegal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Signs Letter of Intent With IMF </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2601103794 Paris AFP in French 2015 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2601103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dakar, 25 Jan (AFP)--Senegal and the IMF have signed 
a "letter of intent" by which Senegal will receive a 
27-billion-CFA franc financial package, official sources 
disclosed in Dakar this evening. The agreement also provides 
for a 40-billion-CFA franc annual grant to Senegal over a period 
of three years as part of the backup measures following the 
devaluation of the CFA franc. 
  A similar letter of intent is expected to be signed between 
Senegal and the World Bank this week, according to World Bank 
sources. Jean-Louis Sarbib, head of the Sahel division of the 
World Bank, told the media that an "agreement has been reached" 
and that "the Senegalese authorities are expected to announce 
this and to give details of the decisions made." 

</TEXT>

