<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Namibia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Full Diplomatic Ties To Be Established With Israel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2801103994 Windhoek DIE REPUBLIKEIN in Afrikaans 24 Jan 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> MB2801103994 </F>
<F P=104>  Windhoek DIE REPUBLIKEIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Afrikaans </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Ties Established With Israel"] </F>
  [Text] On the eve of a visit by a high-level business 
delegation from Jerusalem, the government has announced that 
diplomatic ties will be established with Israel. As early as 
last year, the presence of a Namibian embassy in Israel would 
have been unthinkable because of SWAPO's [South-West African 
People's Organization] open criticism of the Jewish state. 
Shortly after independence, the Namibian Government formally 
established diplomatic ties with the Palestine Liberation 
Organization [PLO] at the ambassadorial level and continued its 
campaign of open support for the organization of Yasir 'Arafat. 
A brief statement issued last week on decisions made at the 
first cabinet meeting in Windhoek for 1994 notes that the 
cabinet has decided to empower Minister of Foreign Affairs Theo 
Ben Gurirab to establish full diplomatic ties with Israel. 
  The cabinet has also given its permission for a high-level 
Israeli business delegation to visit Namibia within the next 
three weeks and for ministries to hold talks with the delegation 
on "areas of interest" for Namibia. The cabinet has taken note 
of the policy objectives being pursued at this stage, concerning 
the Middle East and especially the negotiations between the PLO 
and the Israeli Government. In his New Year's message to the 
diplomatic corps last week, the president, Mr. Sam Nujoma, 
referred to the agreement between Israel and the PLO as one of 
the top "achievements" of 1993. He said that the prospects of 
self-government for Palestine is closer than ever before 
following the signing of the peace agreement. Israel and the 
PLO signed the historic agreement on Palestinian autonomy in 
Gaza and Jericho in Washington on 13 September. In the 
agreement, Israel and the PLO undertook to officially recognize 
each other. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-44253 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr019_d_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-019 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

