<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zimbabwe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference on Restructuring RSA Security Forces Opens </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2701135094 Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio in English 
1100 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2701135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Channel Africa Report" program] </F>
  [Text] A three-day conference aimed at restructuring South 
Africa's security forces has opened in the Zimbabwean capital 
Harare. The conference is being attended by senior military and 
police personnel and officials of the African National Congress 
[ANC] and the Pan-Africanist Congress [PAC]. Trevor Grundy has 
the details: 
  The conference this week is being organized by the Southern 
African Peacekeeping and Peacemaking Project, which operates 
under the auspices of the Institute of International Education 
in New York. The first conference of this kind on South Africa 
was held in Harare in June of last year. Over 70 delegates are 
attending at the Harare International Conference Center and this 
afternoon Justice Richard Goldstone will be talking about the 
prevention of public violence and intimidation in South Africa, 
before and after the elections. Other contributors will be 
General Smit, the deputy commissioner of the South African 
Police Force, Chief Superintendent (Peter Stephens) of Scotland 
Yard, Lieutenant General Pierre Steyn, the former Chief of Staff 
of the SADF [South African Defense Force], Enoch Dambuchena, 
Zimbabwe's former chief justice, plus representatives of the ANC 
and the PAC. 
  The conference opened as President Mugabe was meeting 
President de Klerk for the first time in Botswana. That meeting 
was attended by Defense Minister Moven Mahachi, so in Harare 
someone else has to read his speech. Minister Mahachi praised 
the SADF, the ANC, and the PAC for making attempts to work 
alongside one another to create a national defense force. He 
also called on all soldiers in South Africa to be democratic and 
fair after, as well as before, the April election. It would, he 
said, be a very sad day indeed if the freedom of democratic 
processes -- if the South African Defense Forces should be found 
rejecting the wishes of South Africans, where the process is 
judged to be free and fair by the international community. 
  In a keynote address the current president of the United 
Nations General Assembly warned against widespread violence. 
Ambassador Samuel Insanally of Guyana said that the South 
African law authorities must begin to deal effectively and 
fairly with any threat or disturbance to peace. Deviation at 
this stage, he said, would only lead to disaster and plunge 
South Africa into what he calls dangerous uncertainty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

