<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Zimbabwe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Party Members Join in Bid To Topple Mugabe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2801063494 Gaborone Radio Botswana Network in English 1910 
GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2801063494 </F>
<F P=104>  Gaborone Radio Botswana Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The former head of the Transitional 
Zimbabwe/Rhodesia Government, Mr. Abel Muzorewa, today joined 
opposition leader Mr. Edgar Tekere in an ambitious bid to topple 
President Robert Mugabe's government. The merger was announced 
at a joint news conference in the capital Harare. Mr. Muzorewa, 
aged 67, a retired clergyman of the U.S.-based United Methodist 
Church and leader of the now small opposition party United 
National African Council, and Mr. Tekere, leader of the Zimbabwe 
Unity Movement, ZUM, became co-president of the new party which 
has retained the name ZUM. 
  The retired bishop has made a comeback after retiring from 
politics in 1985 following 10 months of detention by Mr. 
Mugabe's government for alleged subversive activities. He was 
in the limelight in 1970's, when the other black nationalists 
like Mr. Mugabe and Vice President Dr. Joshua Nkomo were either 
exiled or detained by the former Rhodesian rebel leader, Mr. Ian 
Smith. 
  Mr. Muzorewa headed the transitional government to a black 
majority rule set up by Mr. Smith, but lost to Mr. Mugabe in the 
1980 elections because of his alignment to whites. 

</TEXT>

