<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   PAC's Makwetu on Need for Two-Ballot Election </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2701201594 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 1800 
GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2701201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The PAC [Pan-Africanist Congress] and the IFP 
[Inkatha Freedom Party] had the media guessing today when they 
called an unexpected joint media conference at the PAC offices 
in Johannesburg. But according to the leaders of the two 
organizations, today's meeting was in line with ongoing talks 
between the two groups. 
  [Begin recording] [Reporter Nan Roux] The ongoing violence 
and the rejection of a one-ballot system for the coming 
elections. These were the issues discussed at a meeting between 
IFP leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi and PAC President Clarence 
Makwetu. The two leaders said such a system was undemocratic 
and would rob voters of their freedom to choose parties at both 
the provincial and national level. 
  [Makwetu] If we talk of democracy, if I vote on a provincial 
level, and I want to vote differently on a national level I 
should have liberty to do so. It should not be decided by the 
bureaucrat where my vote should lie. 
  [Roux] Mr. Makwetu said the PAC and the IFP had already 
contacted the Democratic Party, the Dikwankwetla Party, and 
others who favor the two-ballot system, in order to work out a 
joint strategy. On the issues of violence, both leaders 
committed themselves to addressing the situation as soon as 
possible for fear that it might jeopardize the entire election 
process. 
  [Makwetu] I support a move by the people directly involved 
in 
the violence sitting together, trying to resolve their 
differences. 
  [Roux] Mr. Makwetu said joint activity between the PAC, the 
IFP, and the ANC, was the only solution. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

