<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violence Reported After Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2801074794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0726 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2801074794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By political correspondent Pierre Claassen, political </F>
correspondent] 
  [Text] Witbank Jan 28 SAPA--Three black National Party [NP] 
supporters had to be removed from their home at the Hlalanikhale 
township, near Witbank, on Friday morning after they had 
welcomed State President F.W. de Klerk to their home. 
  Shortly after President de Klerk and his press and party 
entourage left the township, the men were stoned and security 
sources said they had been removed to safety while negotiations 
through the peace committee attempted to defuse the situation. 
  One of the victims was Mr Simon Maseko. All three men, 
wearing NP paper caps, were waiting for President de Klerk's 
arrival, and later spent some time talking to him before the NP 
leader addressed a gathering crowd, mostly hostile ANC [African 
National Congress] supporters. "They die tonight," one ANC 
supporter was heard to say. 

</TEXT>

