<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies Form Interregional Peace Committee </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2701223094 Paris AFP in French 1835 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2701223094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brazzaville, 27 Jan (AFP)--Today, more than 50 
deputies from the presidential camp and the opposition stemming 
from four southern regions of Congo created an "interregional 
committee" charged with achieving peace because "certain 
elements of the security forces and armed groups of the 
political coalitions are sowing terror" among the citizens. 
  Government radio reported that the committee of deputies was 
set up following a meeting of representatives from the main 
opposition party, the Congolese Movement for Democracy and 
Integral Development [MCDDI] of Bernard Kolelas, and President 
Pascal Lissouba's party, and the Pan-African Union for Social 
Democracy, UPADES. 
  The MCDDI activists are mostly from the Pool Region, around 
the capital, while those from UPADES are from the regions of 
Niari, Bouenza, and Lekoumou. The committee, which is headed by 
Simon Diassakoula, an MCDDI deputy, is charged with initiating 
peace efforts in the four regions and the capital, where their 
citizens are fighting in the southern district. 
  Those regions were affected by acts of violence, mainly in 
June and July 1994 during the first round of the early 
legislative elections, which were challenged by the opposition. 
At least 30 people were reportedly killed during those events. 
In Brazzaville, about 115 deaths were reported in the fighting, 
which took place from mid-December 1993 to early January between 
the militias of the opposition and presidential camp. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-44275 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr019_d_94001" </HT>


