<H3> <TI>   Guangdong To Manage Sri Lankan Sugar Factory </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3012161193 Beijing XINHUA in English 1444 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> OW3012161193 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Colombo, December 30 (XINHUA) -- China's Guangdong 
International Economic and Technological Cooperation Company 
today took over the management of the Palwat Sugar Factory, one 
of the biggest sugar producers in Sri Lanka. 
  According to the contract signed by the two sides today in 
Colombo, the management of the sugar factory with an annual 
production of 4,600 tons will be undertaken by 16 Chinese 
managers and experts. 
  The signing ceremony was attended by Sri Lankan Minister of 
Plantations Rupa Karunatilleke, Agricultural Minister R.M. 
Dharmadasa Banda and Chinese Ambassador Zhang Chengli. 
  The factory, set up in the southeastern Uwa Province in 
1986, 
had been managed by a British company which has come under 
attack by local people and press reports for environmental 
reasons before the Chinese take-over, the first of its kind in 
economic cooperation between Sri Lanka and China. 

</TEXT>

